# 2. The `for` Statement (Loop)

### Example Code

```c
for (fahr = 0; fahr <= 300; fahr = fahr + 20)
    printf("%3d %6.1f\n", fahr, (5.0/9.0)*(fahr-32));
```

### Structure of a `for` loop

```
for (initialization; condition; increment)
```

| Part           | Meaning                      |
| -------------- | ---------------------------- |
| initialization | Runs once before loop starts |
| condition      | Checked every iteration      |
| increment      | Runs after each loop         |

---

### Execution Flow

```
Start
  |
fahr = 0
  |
Check fahr <= 300
  |
True
  |
Run printf
  |
fahr = fahr + 20
  |
Repeat
```

Loop stops when the condition becomes **false**.

---

### Linux Internals Example

In Linux kernel code, similar loops iterate through structures.

Example (conceptual):

```c
for (i = 0; i < NR_TASKS; i++) {
    if (task[i] != NULL)
        schedule(task[i]);
}
```

Here the kernel is looping through **all process entries**.

So the **temperature example teaches the same looping concept used in kernel scheduling**.

